<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-140-089 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 044 676</DOCID><JOURNAL>Iandamp;CS (Instrumentation andamp; Control Systems)  June 1991 v64 n6 p77(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>PLCs help flour mill double production capacity. (Amber Milling)(Cover Story)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Grundy, Ken.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Production rates 15 to 20 percent above the original target wereachieved when Amber Milling automated and expanded its durum wheatflour mill, which is the largest in the US.andP;  The mill is nowcompletely automated, which doubled its production capacity.andO;Added in the expansion were new loading, feeding, and packagingsystems.andP;  All process streams in the plant have real-time control.andO;The control system is made up of two 80386-based computers and aSquare D SY/MAX 600 programmable controller.andP;  All milling systemfunctions are monitored and controlled by the programmablecontroller, which uses 14 local and remote I/O racks.andP;  There arethree control dta communications networks.andP;  A Square D SY/LINKnetwork is used by the computers to communicate with theprogrammable controllers.andP;  The software includes preventivemaintenance by monitoring the time-in-use of key systemcomponents.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Amber Milling Co. (Automation)Square D Co. (Products).andO;Product:   Square D SY/MAX 650 (Control board) (Usage)SY/LINK (Computer network) (Usage).andO;Topic:     Process ControlProgrammable ControllersFactory ManagementProductionPreventive Maintenance.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>